segments.text: Army guys, of course, still had some khakis left over.
But, you know, it was cheap, whatever it was.
And did you all get regular haircuts?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, you didn't see any long hairs.
What did you all come to assume were the unwritten but clearly understood rules for classroom behavior?
I think...
that certainly were unwritten, but I think they were a carryover from where you came from school, you know, your high school.
And in those days, there weren't any rowdy classes.
I think the veterans were there by and large to get an education.
They weren't there to make any kind of post.
I do think that the veterans probably had a quieting
influence on anybody who wanted to be writing.
I don't think we ever had any discipline problems in class.
I never remember one.
Do you remember some pranks or jokes that ever occurred in any class?
Not in class, no.
There were always stuff, you know, off campus.
I mean, you know, out of class.
But I don't, we were a pretty serious group.
I don't remember any.
What about some faculty members that you came to respect highly during all of your years there?
During all my years?
All your student years.
I have good recollections of more of my junior-senior years.
Not so much the business faculty.
I would say they were, by and large, mediocre.
But the liberal arts faculty, I remember a feeling that I was really learning something there.
I liked English.
I had some good English professors.
I can't remember names right now.
Who was the head of the English department?
Gosh, I can't remember.
Was it Cofer?
No.
D.B.
Cofer?
I can't remember.
But I do have a distinct feeling that I got a good liberal arts education.
Those guys, the liberal arts people, for some reason I had the feeling that they had been there.
They had some tenure, more so than the business school.
Do you remember some nicknames for some faculty members?
No.
There were some, but I just can't remember.
Let's see, what about some student pranks in the dormitory or anywhere else that you knew about?
About the only thing, people get drowned out occasionally, which I've already explained.
Not much more than that, and there wasn't a whole lot of that.
Occasionally guys come in drunk and raise a ruckus, but I expect less of that than a lot of other places.
Where did you and your buddies that first year or so go on a Saturday night for a good time?
Well, first of all, we were constrained by lack of money.
But not having cars, we couldn't leave.
We couldn't leave Bryan College Station.
We would go to the movies.
We would go out and drink some beer.
Of course, those who were older could do that without a problem.
Where did you go to drive?
Oh, there was a little...
beer joint halfway between Bryan and College Station, kind of at the Y down there, and we'd go down there and drink beer.
There really wasn't a whole lot to do.
Movies, and that's it.
Did you go to Uncle Ed's?
Hard Liquors?
I went out to Hard Liquors, yeah.
Describe it, as far as you remember.
I really don't have much recollection of it.
How many people could it seat?
Oh, gosh.
Was it a
Maybe 40 or 50.
Was it a wild, noisy place?
No, just good times, but not wild and noisy.
I don't remember it being wild and noisy.
And did they attempt to not serve beer to underage people?
Well, since we were of age, I never paid much attention to them not serving.
I don't ever remember anybody being refused.
Did people get drunk?
Oh yeah, yeah, people got drunk, but I never got real bad.

I do remember there was a, he was a fellow who had been on the team of, championship team of 39, and he was one of these guys who, he was apparently a great football player, but he could never get away from college, and he'd come back and he lived out there, and he was a drunk, and we used to feel so sorry for him.
Did you, that first year or so, did you ever go to the clay pits?
Don't know where they are.
Okay.
That's an area, I don't know in what era, but it was west, south of the campus, across the railroad in somebody's pasture, and it was an old pit where they had dug some clay for building purposes.
And there was sleazy water in there, and apparently that's where they'd go, eight or ten guys, drink beer, maybe go skinny dipping,
No, I don't know about that.
In those years, all of your student years, were you ever aware of a bootlegger in Brazos County?
I heard of him, but I didn't know about him.
If anybody wanted liquor, he drove across the river.
Did you all call it Whiskey Bridge?
I don't think we called it.
I know that name, but I don't think we had it.
It was just over the river.
Did any of the veterans bring alcohol back into the dormitory?
Not much.
There was some.
but not much.
And not hard liquor, really, that I remember.
Occasionally some beer, but there really wasn't much of that.
What were the, while we're on this point, what were the other, what were people smoking?
There were a lot of pipe smoking, cigarette smoking, not much cigars.
But a lot of people did smoke.
Probably, you know, a lot more than they do now, I'm sure.
Churned tobacco?
The rodeo team did, yeah.
I remember one time the rodeo guys all lived in one dormitory.
I want to call it Pazell, but I don't know whether it was or not.
It was right by Sabisa Hall.
And they all lived in that same dormitory.
And most of them did.
And one time a guy had a rope that he wanted to stretch.
And so he had a car.
And he tied the rope around the bumper of the car and the other side to a tree and then took it up tight, you know, to stretch the rope.
And the campus policemen at that time, the campus cops were not the caliber they are now.
They were really, I don't know where they got them.
But they ticketed this guy for having bad brakes because they thought he had tied his car up to keep him from rolling down the street.
That was the mentality of the campus cops at that time.
But the rodeo guys, they were a tough group.
They were a lot of fun.
But they dressed just the way rodeo guys always have dressed, I guess.
The MSC didn't exist.
Oh, Guy and Hall.
There were movies there, too.
Casual movies in Guy and Hall, yeah.
That's where I first saw it.
We've never been late.
But I don't remember going to Guy and Hall a whole lot.
And maybe one of the reasons is, of course, I worked at WTOL, and then I went to work on the battalion.
I mean, working in the battalion, you just didn't have any time at all to go off to movies and do that.
Alright, now why did you get involved with the battalion?
You weren't going to be a journalist were you?
No, I had no ambitions to be a journalist.
I'm not sure how I got involved.
I know I paid a little bit more.
I think I was making like maybe 50 cents an hour at the radio station.
Maybe I got 60 or 65 at the battalion.
And for a while I worked at both places.
I didn't get paid in the battalion the first time.
But then
The battalion offered to pay me, and so I quit the radio station and went on the battalion.
And you were not getting any journalism course credit for either one?
Oh, no, no.
But that, I have said this before, that is probably the best experience I had with working on the battalion.
Explain.
The director of student publications, a man by the name of Roland Bing.
Bing?
Bing, B-I-N-G.
He was an interesting man.
He was, at that time, he was a bachelor.

He worked, he had, he was slightly crippled, and he lived in YMCA, and he had been, he was an Aggie, and he had been in World War II, and because he was somewhat crippled, he had limited duty, and he ended up coaching a black football team at Randolph Field, which apparently, and he got all the good black football players
And his team beat everybody.
And he did not need to go into the Army.
He went in.
He had to fight his way to get in.
Well, he came out and went to A&M.
And he was in charge of student publication.
And he ran that operation as well as anybody, I think, ever could.
And he made it a challenge to us to put out a paper without mistakes in it.
What did you all think the function of the battalion was?
We were very independent.
What was its importance?
It's important.
We were the newspaper, and we prided ourselves on being very independent.
And we were.
They never checked our editorials, our news stories.
But Bing, we always called him Bing, conveyed to us the responsibility that we had of running our own newspaper.
And he would say, as long as you do it responsibly, you don't need to worry about anything.
Do it right.
And we honored that.
Did y'all print stories that were positive as often as you did negative?
Yeah, we tried to be very, we won several college newspaper awards while we were there.
And while we were, one of the things that we kicked off, I don't know whether they do it now, but we sponsored the Southwest Conference Sportsmanship Award.
That was a first for the battalion.
But we did win a number of awards.

But he would put, Bing would take the paper and put it up on the bulletin board and circle in red any grammatical error that we made or where we were editorializing in something that should have been a news story or where it was obviously slanting the news.
He would point it out.
And our goal was to put up a paper that Bing couldn't put a red mark on.
Where was the
Where were the offices?
Goodwin Hall.
Goodwin Hall.
And the press was in the basement of Goodwin Hall.
So it was actually printed there?
It was printed there, and we set our own, we didn't set our own type, we set our own headlines, and we made up the paper down there on our own.
There were some really good fellows that worked down in the press, but we put the paper to bed.
How many issues per week?
Five a week.
So just the weekdays?
Weekdays only.
Weekdays only.
And it was morning or afternoon?
Let's see.
I should have that.
It was afternoon, because it took us the whole evening to run the press roll.
I think it came out in the afternoon, early, mid-afternoon.
And did you say a while ago you don't remember how you exactly got involved?
No, I really don't.
I think it was maybe somebody on W-Talk.
Also worked in the paper and said, hey, they need somebody over here who can do this, you know, and I went over and worked both places.
But all student publications worked out of it.
What were some important stories that you remember?
Oh, gosh.
I got in trouble with the administration one time, and I don't know, I guess it was when I was a junior, maybe.
And for some reason or other, they cut the Christmas vacations
You didn't get off on a Christmas vacation until like the 22nd or 23rd.
You just had a few days.
And my brother, who came the day after I did, he was married.
He was an architect, and he could draw.
And I got him to draw a cartoon, which we put on the front page.
And it showed this Aggie standing knee-deep in the snow with his bag.
And Santa Claus saying, you should have been home for Christmas by now.
And he says, I couldn't.
I go to A&M and they wouldn't let me out.
And Dr. Harrington called me into his office and read me the riot act.
But they were wrong.
And I didn't worry about that.
They never said anything about it.
But it really upset the administration.
Was it during that time when the Corps marched on Dr. Gilchrist?
No, that was before.
That was 46 or 47.
I thought so.
No, this was later.
What were some other big issues that you all... Oh, well, I told you how I got in trouble editorializing against Midnight Yale practice.
That was a mistake.
And it was a signed editorial.
Oh yeah, they knew who wrote the editorials.
I don't remember any big stories.
Of course, a big story was whenever the guys from the University of Texas came over and tried to firebomb the bonfire.
which at that time was built on the parade ground outside of, I don't know what they call it now, but it was outside Goodwin Hall.
The drill field.
Drill field, okay.
It's now Simpson Drill Field.
Simpson, okay.
Let's talk about Bonfire.
Do you remember Bonfire your freshman year?
Since it was in you, you didn't see it.
Did you veterans get involved at all?
Not as much as the Corps did, but it wasn't as big an organized thing then as it has been in recent years.
What was the Bonfire made of?
It wasn't big logs like they do now.
It was more whatever they could gather up.
It was pretty big, but I mean, compared to other schools.
Where did they gather it?
Down, you know, off campus.
But I don't remember.
And how did they procure that?
I don't have any.
I'm sure it was illegal.
I don't remember.
See, on the battalion, I didn't have time to do that.
We just would comment on it.
We didn't have to work on it.
And what was the pinnacle of Bonfire?
Oh, it was a night house.
And it was supposedly, was it painted orange in your day?
I don't remember it being painted.
I'm sure it had marks from UT on it, but I don't specifically remember.
Do you remember in any of your years did you help gather up any of the material?
No, because I was working on it.
All right, now describe this bombing.
Well, the stack had been pretty well built, and battalion officers were up on the second floor of Goodman Hall overlooking the drill field.
And
It was just a day or two before, and we heard this airplane.
Daytime?
It was daytime.
Oh, yeah.
I heard this airplane, and it came over, and it came real low.
And they were dropping things out, which turned out to be some kind of bottle-top cocktail.
I don't know whether they were on fire.
They had to have been on fire, I guess.
Well, they thought they could set the thing off, and that was what they couldn't have.
But we were all very frustrated, shaking fists in the air, because the airplane might have, as I remember, more than one pass over trying to drop things on it.
And I mean, Pete, we were furious, you know, because we felt so impotent.
And nobody got out a gun?
No, no, nobody did anything like that.
Was it a biplane?
No, it was a single-wing plane.
And the story we got was that, you know, you knew where it came from.
So somebody in the administration called over to Austin and alerted the police over there, and they picked the guys up when they landed.
I don't know what happened, but...
But it was a big excitement.
We didn't have many things happening.
Who were the key administrative leaders of A&M during your undergraduate days?
The one that I remember, of course, Dr. Harrington, Dean Penberthy.
Spike White, he was the student activities athlete, all that sort of intramural sports type thing.
Can you describe them in personality?
Dr. Harrington?
Yeah, he was...
I have to be careful here to think of Dr. Harrington's name as I knew him later, but he was well respected.
Chemistry faculty member?
Yes, he was chemistry.
And I think there was a feeling of respect for him and the office at that time.
I presume that still exists.
But he was, by that time, he's the president.
I think he was, he may have been dean of arts and sciences.
I didn't go that high up in the hierarchy at that time.
But he was the one that, in my mind, stands out because he's the one that read the right act to me when I put that cartoon in the paper.
And then Penberthy.
Penberthy was director of, dean of management at that time, it was just Dean Penberthy.
It wasn't a particularly forceful kind of fella.
But did you respect him?
I think we tolerated him.
The veterans didn't pay much attention to him, to tell the truth.
I think he felt the veterans were more than he could handle because they respected him, but if they wanted to do something, they didn't.
A&M changed because they didn't have the control over the student body like they'd had before.
And of course, then the commandant of cadets, he was a big factor.
When I first got there, I think it was Joe Davis was the commandant.
And Joe was a good fellow.
But the administration didn't give him much slack.
The better one, the best one, in my recollection, was Hayden Bogart.
Describe him.
Oh, he was a tiger.
He'd been a Marine enlisted man in World War I.
He was then, of course, went to West Point.
He was tough.
He ran, and my experience with him is when I, after I got into the Corps, he would not tolerate shoddiness in any respect.
There'd been a good bit of hazing going on.
He tried to put a lead on it, and it was fairly successful.
He just wouldn't tolerate it.
He was introduced to the honor code, which was well respected.
He was tough as nails and swore like a Marine.
The guys were kind of afraid of him, but he wanted them to be.
But he was a good man.
He was a good friend.
He didn't kowtow to the administration like
former Commandants had.
Former Commandants were not, they were employees of the state, whereas the Boatner was active duty Army members.
And that changed the relationship.
And so he pretty well ran the Corps.
Later, were you and your buddies surprised when he took over that Korean prisoner of war camp where there had been a riot and everything?
I don't think we were surprised.
but we felt that he was probably the best man for the job.
A sidebar to that, I was, after I graduated, I went into the second division in Korea, and had been there about, oh, almost a year, and I was due to rotate home.
I may have told you this story.
I was due to rotate home.
Unbeknownst to me, General Boatner, Colonel Boatner had been promoted to Brigadier General, and I was in Japan on R&R,
And he got assigned to 2nd Division Command, Assistant Division Commander.
So I went back to Korea from R&R.
I didn't know he was there.
And I arrived in my battalion, back of the truck, two day broke the beard, covered with dust.
And I jumped out of the back and the battalion commander came up and he said, there's some general in our division who wants to see you right now.
He said, take my jeep and get down to him.
Went to the other battalion commander and gave the jeep to the lieutenant that he's living in.
So I went down and I didn't
I was trying to think what I'd done in Japan that would merit, you know, what I felt was coming.
And I got down there and got a hold of his aide.
And I told him who I was.
And I said, the assistant division commander has asked to see me.
And he said, yes, he wants to see you.
I said, well, boy, I'm in trouble.
So I went down and he was living in a truck, you know, with a bed on the back of it.
And who comes out of the general boat?
And he looked at me and I'm standing there and I have this dust all over me and I'm not shaved.
And he tore me up one side and down the other.
What kind of specter are you?
What do you mean coming in and reporting to me looking like you've come out of a ditch?
I mean, for about five minutes.
Then he laughed.
He said, come in and have a drink.
So we went in and had a drink with him and he said, I've been given the job of having division history written.
And he said,
He knew me from the battalion.
He said, I think that's something you could do.
And I didn't want to do it because I was due to go home.
And I scuffled around a little bit and he sensed that I was reluctant.
And he said, go back and think about it and give me a call tomorrow.
So I went back to the battalion.
I got to the battalion and my bags were packed.
I had already been transferred.
And so I went back down and he laughed and he said,
Now, this was about July or August of 1951.
And he said, you get this done, I'll see you get home for Christmas.
So he gave me a driver, and just carte blanche to do it.
And I ended up with a couple artists and photographers and what have you.
And I drove all around the division, and I wrote that history.
And so I carried it back.
He never asked to see it.
I carried it in, and I gave him the whole manuscript.
And he said, okay.
He said, they'll come back in about three days.
I'm back three days.
He said, okay.
He said, now I want you to get published.
And he gave me the name of a colonel going to the Far East Command.
He said, you go over there and tell them Hayden Boatner said to put you together with somebody that can publish this book in Japan.
So my entourage, we got over to Japan, put something with VIP quarters and gave us a staff car.
I went in to see this colonel.
And I said, Hayden Boatner said for me to tell you this.
And so he said, be accustomed.
He said, okay.
And he put us with the Fari printing company that printed the Fari's edition of Newsweek magazine.
And they had English line types.
So they put the thing together, and we went in 10 o'clock in the morning, proofread until mid-afternoon, went out and went back.
And we just lived our life a ride, you know, for about five, six weeks.
And they put the thing on.
I called on the phone, and by this time it was the middle of December.
I called Boatner on the phone, and I said, we've got the first production, the first books off the line.
And by this time, I had a captain working for me.
Well, I was first lieutenant, but the captain worked for me.
The captain ended up, he was living with some Japanese girl.
But he said, you tell Captain, whatever his name was, he said, you tell him to stay there and make the arrangements to ship these books to the addresses that we're going to give him.
And he said, you go over and see Colonel so-and-so.
Far East Command said you're to get home by Christmas.
In four hours, I was on an airplane.
And then the follow-up to that is, I went to Fort Knox.
And I did make it home for Christmas.
I went to Fort Knox, finished armored school, and at that time he'd been sent to coaching.
And he called me and wanted me to be his aide at coaching.
But I'd already just taken another job as an aide to another officer at another job.
So I couldn't do it.
It was a big decision, because I really kind of wanted to go.
But the guy I was aide to was the commander general of all the armored corps, and I figured I'd better stay with him.
But anyway, we were good friends.
I used to see him when he lived here, and then to a day he died.
Let's see, back on campus.
I got away from it a while ago, and if you have an answer to this, typist, put it back in chronological, go back in the right time.
People smoked tobacco, and they drank some beer, and a little bit of strong alcohol.
Yeah, but not much.
What other, did y'all even know any other...
Drugs existed?
Absolutely not.
I don't think there was a tea school full of drugs on the campus outside of the medics.
It was just not there.
And in that first year or so, where did you and your buddies get dates?
I made a couple trips up to TSCW.
There's something else now, I don't know what it is, but up there.
TWU.
TWU, okay.
Mainly through there, I think.
Because those girls would come down, you know.
They'd empty out a dormitory and put the girls in there.
Did you have any of those dates?
Oh, yeah.
Describe the routine.
How would the girls get down there?
I'm trying to think.
Was it on the bus or the train?
No, it wasn't the train.
It must have been the bus or maybe cars.
I don't remember how they got there.
We didn't have a transportation.
Many of us did.
And I didn't.
But...
I don't remember how they got there, but anyway, most of them stayed in dormitories.
They'd clear out a whole dormitory.
You'd just have to go and move somewhere else.
And, oh, it was a great time.
How were those young women treated?
Oh, marvelous.
You know, because there were still relatively few of them on campus, even when they'd come in from the dances.
And they'd bring their friends, too.
Oh, they got the royal treatment.
It's not like today where you take it for granted.
Now, I've heard about
Some routines in the dormitory of a moose pod or beast bucket where there would be a kind of a game.
Who got stuck with the worst date?
No, I don't remember that.
All dates were good.
There weren't any bad ones.
And where were the dances held?
Sabisa.
Oh, yeah.
Sabisa got all decorated up.
They had a band.
The Aggieland Orchestra would come in and play.
What did you all think about the Aggieland Orchestra?
Oh, we loved them.
They were good.
They played our kind of music.
I keep thinking that ought to be recreated.
They don't have it now?
No.
That would be a splendid thing.
What was his name, Turner?
Yeah.
Bill Turner.
I think it was.
Oh, it was a very credible dance thing.
Yeah, and they played concerts across the state, I've learned.
Do you remember taking any dates to football games?
No, I don't.
I must have, but I don't remember.
And you veterans didn't get involved with Reveley?
Oh, you get up in the morning, you ain't got Reveley?
Or the dog?
Or the dog, either one.
No, we didn't get involved.
Of course, if Reveley came around, he got same treatment on our side of the fences.
Is that right?
Oh, yeah.
Let's see, did you go to any basketball games?
Yes, I know I did.
And they were in... DeWare?
DeWare, yeah.
Describe them.
noisy, hot, and we didn't win many.
What did you and your buddies think about Yell Leaders?
Oh, we liked them, yeah.
They had civilian, non-reg Yell Leaders also, and they were a very closely knit group, and everybody liked them.
We elected them, as I remember.
And football and basketball games, did you veterans
mix in with the core?
Yeah, there wasn't any distinction.
Were you all aware of any special courses or any kind of gimmicks for athletes?
No.
They took the same courses?
They took the same courses, had the same props, everything.
I don't even know that they got any kind of special counseling.
They didn't make it.
The married veterans, describe what you remember about where they were living and the routine for them.
Okay.
Well, their routine on campus was basically, you know, like the other non-regs.
And their wives worked all over campus.
I don't think the school could have gotten by without all those wives because the school had grown so rapidly and there were so many jobs to be done and those young girls, you know, they'd
this field in every position you can think of.

They lived, some of them lived in town, but most of them, I think, lived in the old converted army barracks that were over there, I don't know how to, off Texas Avenue, down from where the Ramada is, back in there.
And they were abysmal buildings.
All right, now, weren't there also some down near the south end of Kyle Field?
There were some houses, but those were, I think, were the project houses.
Oh, so they were that, all right.
And were there some veterans housing also near the Northgate area, stuck in there?
Not that I remember.
Married veterans, not that I remember.
I think it was all kind of down from the Ramada back in there.
College Butte.
Yeah, the College Butte.
There were a lot of them.
And it was great to go over there and get a home cooked meal once in a while.
We had friends.
Was there a veterans extracurricular organization?
If there was, I don't remember, but they were pretty active.
